1 MLE: Poisson Regression

What first? We start with some fake data…

We need a population (here 10000 observations).

n <- 10000

# We set true parameters for \beta_0 and \beta_1

beta0 <- 1
beta1 <- 0.5

# and generate an independent variable X
set.seed(2021)
X <- rnorm(n, 0, 1)

Now we can generate lambda (aka \(\lambda\) on slide 13) via the exponential response function:

\[ \lambda_i = \exp(X_i\beta) = \exp(\mu_i) \Rightarrow 0 < \lambda \]

Here mu is the linear predictor. As with logit and probit models last week, we need to transform the linear predictor, but this time with a different response function. The exponential response function ensures that for any value of \(X\) and \(\beta\), the systematic component is reparameterized to be greater than 0.

exp_resp <- function(beta0, beta1, X) {
  lambda <- exp(beta0 + beta1 * X)
  return(lambda)
}

lambda <- exp_resp(
  beta0 = beta0,
  beta1 = beta1,
  X = X
)

Let’s quickly plot what we just did:

Base R

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))

2 Poisson MLE

The Poisson PDF for a single observation:

\[ f_{Poisson}(y_{i}|\lambda) = \begin{cases} \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^{y_{i}}}{y_{i}!} & \text{ for } \lambda > 0\text{ and }y_{i}=0,1,\ldots\\ 0 & otherwise \end{cases} \]

The probability density of all the data (i.e., \(N\) observations, given that \(Y_i\) and \(Y_j\) are independent conditional on \(X\) for all \(i\not= j\) and identically distributed) is the product of all \(N\) individual observations:

\[ Pr(Y|\lambda) = \prod_{i=1}^{N} \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^{y_{i}}}{y_{i}!} \]

This is the likelihood. But as usual, we prefer the log-likelihood:

\[ \ln L(\lambda|Y) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_{i} ln(\lambda_i) - \lambda_i) \]

Replacing \(\lambda\) with the linear component (i.e. \(X_{i}\beta\)) gives us the likelihood function of our model:

\[ \ln L(\beta|Y) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_{i} (X_{i}\beta) -e^{X_{i}\beta})\\ \]

Program the Poisson log-likelihood function (cf. slide 13)

## Poisson MLE

# Log Likelihood
pois_ll <- function(X, Y, theta) {
  beta0 <- theta[1]
  beta1 <- theta[2]

  logl <- sum(Y * (beta0 + beta1 * X) - exp(beta0 + beta1 * X))
  return(logl)
}

As the linear predictor mu is reparameterized with exp(), we can again estimate theta unbounded, but ensure that counts will not be negative.

Find the MLE using optimx:

# Starting Values
stval <- c(0, 0)

# Optimize
res <-
  optimx(
    stval,
    pois_ll,
    Y = Y,
    X = X,
    control = list(maximize = T)
  )
## Maximizing -- use negfn and neggr
## Warning in max(logpar): kein nicht-fehlendes Argument für max; gebe -Inf zurück
## Warning in min(logpar): kein nicht-fehlendes Argument für min; gebe Inf zurück

4 Likelihood Ratio Test (Overdispersion)

The likelihood ratio test is a test to compare two models, one of which is a special case of the other (Restricted and Unrestricted Model…).

Let L1 be the likelihood for the null model with m parameters and L2 be the likelihood for the alternative model with n parameters, n > m. One can show that when \(n \to \infty\), \(-2 \times log(\frac{L1}{L2})\) converges to the \(\chi^2\) distribution with \(k = n - m\) degrees of freedom. See also DeGroot and Schervish (2012): pp. 543–544.

Thus, \(LRT = -2*log(L1) + 2*log(L2)\)

L1 <- logLik(m1) # Log Likelihood of model 1
L2 <- logLik(m2) # Log Likelihood of model 2

LRT <- -2 * L1 + 2 * L2 # converges to chi^2 distribution

# Reject H0 if ... What is our H0 here?

LRT > qchisq(0.95, df = 1)
## [1] TRUE

As usually we can interpret the results better if we look at meaningful quantities of interest.

We look at the model from the Eck/Hultman paper.

m2 <-
  glm.nb(
    os_best ~ intensity_dyad + auto + demo + govt + prior_os,
    data = dta,
    control = glm.control(maxit = 100)
  )

5.1 Simulate Parameters

Remember the steps?

Steps for Simulating Parameters (Estimation Uncertainty):

  1. Get the coefficients from the regression (gamma_hat)
  2. Get the variance-covariance matrix (V_hat)
  3. Set up a multivariate normal distribution N(gamma_hat,V_hat)
  4. Draw from the distribution nsim times
nsim <- 1000

# 1. get the coefficients
gamma_hat <- coef(m2)

# 2. Get the variance-covariance matrix
V_hat <- vcov(m2)

# 3. Set up a multivariate normal distribution N(gamma_hat, V_hat)
# 4. Draw from the distribution nsim times
S <- mvrnorm(nsim, gamma_hat, V_hat)

5.2 Calculate Expected Values

Next step: Set up interesting scenarios.

Autocracies

scenario1 <-
  cbind(
    1, # Intercept
    median(dta$intensity_dyad, na.rm = TRUE), # median of civil war (dyadic)
    1, # autocracy
    0, # democracy
    median(dta$govt, na.rm = TRUE), # median of one-sided violence by government
    mean(dta$prior_os, na.rm = TRUE) # mean of prior one-sided violence
  )

Democracies

scenario2 <- cbind(

  median(dta$intensity_dyad, na.rm = TRUE),
  0,
  1,

  mean(dta$prior_os, na.rm = TRUE)

Anocracies

scenario3 <- cbind(
  1,
  median(dta$intensity_dyad, na.rm = TRUE),
  0,
  0,
  median(dta$govt, na.rm = TRUE),
  mean(dta$prior_os, na.rm = TRUE)
)
Xbeta1 <- S %*% t(scenario1)

Xbeta2 <- S %*% t(scenario2)

Xbeta3 <- S %*% t(scenario3)

To get expected values for lambda, we need to plug in the Xbeta values into the response function

lambda1 <- exp(Xbeta1)

lambda2 <- exp(Xbeta2)

lambda3 <- exp(Xbeta3)

Now we need an additional step:

Plug the lambda and theta into the negative binomial distribution. And then we average over the fundamental uncertainty for expected values. Please have a look at the King, Tomz, and Wittenberg (2000) article from Week 7 again for further information.

Get the theta.

theta <- m2$theta

exp_auto <-
  sapply(lambda1, function(x) {
    mean(rnbinom(1000, size = theta, mu = x))
  })

exp_demo <-
  sapply(lambda2, function(x) {
    mean(rnbinom(1000, size = theta, mu = x))
  })

exp_ano <-
  sapply(lambda3, function(x) {
    mean(rnbinom(1000, size = theta, mu = x))
  })
